<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Follett ice machines</p>
    <h2>An independent Pennsylvania manufacturer that owns the chewable-ice and healthcare-dispenser categories.</h2>

    <p>Follett LLC is an independent commercial ice equipment manufacturer based in Easton, Pennsylvania, founded in 1948. They are not part of Welbilt (which owns Manitowoc) or Ali Group (which owns Scotsman and Ice-O-Matic). They compete in two specific segments where they hold strong positions: chewable Chewblet nugget ice for healthcare and premium beverage operations, and ice and water dispensers for hospital patient floors, dialysis units, and clinical environments. In LA's healthcare-heavy commercial appliance landscape, Follett is the brand we see at Cedars-Sinai outpatient clinics, UCLA Medical Center facilities, Kaiser locations, dialysis centers, and assisted-living buildings.</p>

    <p>Follett's product lines fall into four families. Chewblet ice machines (Ice Pro Chewblet, 7Series, 25Series, Maestro Plus dispensers, Symphony Plus healthcare dispensers) produce the soft chewable nugget ice that's their flagship. Cube-format units exist but are secondary to the chewable line. Specialty water dispensing infrastructure for healthcare. Cleaning chemistry (Sanitizer 2.0) for the dispenser lines. The diagnostic approach on Follett equipment differs from Hoshizaki KM-Edge or Manitowoc Indigo cubers because the chewable mechanism has fundamentally different failure modes than mold-style cubers.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, applied toward repair. BHGS #A49573 and EPA 608 Universal #1346255700410 for sealed-system work. We service Follett ice machines and dispensers across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside counties.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Product lines we service</p>
    <h2>Chewable, dispenser, and specialty Follett platforms.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Chewblet ice machines (Ice Pro, 7Series, 25Series, Maestro Plus, Symphony Plus)</h3>
    <p>The flagship line. Chewblet produces soft chewable nugget-format ice through an extruded auger mechanism rather than the cube-mold method used by Hoshizaki and Manitowoc cubers. Common service items: auger drive gear motor (year 5 to 8 typical wear), auger flights themselves (year 8 to 10), dispense valve actuators on dispenser variants, water inlet valve, condenser coil cleaning. The auger is the mechanical heart of Chewblet and gets the most wear. We carry replacement gear motors for current 7Series and 25Series and stock dispense valve assemblies for Symphony Plus and Maestro Plus.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Symphony Plus healthcare dispensers (hospital floors, dialysis, clinics)</h3>
    <p>Hospital-grade ice and water dispensers with antimicrobial agitator, optional UV sanitization, and Follett's Sanitizer 2.0 cleaning cycle. Common at Cedars-Sinai, UCLA, Kaiser, and most LA-area dialysis centers. Service items: control board (year 8 to 12), dispense actuator wear from high-cycle hospital use, water inlet, drain pump on integrated drain models, UV bulb replacement on UV-equipped units. Symphony Plus units in healthcare see continuous duty cycle which produces different wear patterns than restaurant operations.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Maestro Plus restaurant dispensers</h3>
    <p>Restaurant and beverage version of the Symphony platform. Same core mechanical architecture as Symphony Plus minus the healthcare-specific sanitization features. Common at higher-end LA restaurants, hotel pool bars, cocktail-focused operations where Chewblet ice is part of the menu specification. Service items mirror Symphony Plus: dispense valve, control board, water inlet, auger components.</p>

    <h3 class="syre-h3">7Series and 25Series compact countertop</h3>
    <p>Lower-volume Chewblet machines for office break rooms, small clinics, dental offices, executive suites. Single-piece countertop or undercounter form factors. Service items: auger gear motor, water inlet valve, condenser cleaning. Compact form factor means parts access is tighter than full-size units; allow extra labor time on these calls.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Common Follett failures</p>
    <h2>What we see on Follett service calls.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Auger gear motor failure (year 5 to 8 typical)</h3>
    <p>The auger gear motor drives the extrusion that produces Chewblet nugget ice. Years of continuous duty cycle wear the gear teeth and degrade the motor windings. Symptom: machine runs but ice production drops or stops, sometimes with audible motor strain or grinding. Replacement runs $385 to $625 with parts and labor depending on platform.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Dispense valve actuator wear</h3>
    <p>On Symphony Plus and Maestro Plus dispensers, the dispense valve actuator cycles every time a customer or patient operates the dispenser. In high-volume healthcare settings (hospital floors with dozens of patients) the actuator can see 200+ cycles per day. Year 4 to 7 typical replacement. $245 to $385 installed.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Control board failure (year 8 to 12 on Symphony, year 6 to 10 on Maestro)</h3>
    <p>Symphony Plus control boards are robust because the platform is designed for healthcare reliability. Maestro Plus boards see slightly more variable failure timing. We diagnose with multimeter at board input and output; replacement runs $485 to $785 depending on model and current parts availability.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Water inlet valve and condenser coil (annual maintenance)</h3>
    <p>Standard maintenance items across all Follett platforms. LA water hardness (300 to 400 mg/L TDS on LADWP supply) accelerates scaling on the water inlet valve and the evaporator coil. Annual cleaning + valve inspection extends component life noticeably. We bundle this with any service call when the unit is open for other work.</p>
  </div>
</section>

